WEBVTT

00:00.866 --> 00:08.353
So our theme as you know and as you heard is real joy, pursuing satisfaction in God.

00:09.795 --> 00:13.718
So we're talking here about Christian joy.

00:14.920 --> 00:16.141
It's supernatural joy.

00:18.323 --> 00:26.471
People outside this room, all around town, all around the world, unbelieving people experience natural joy.

00:26.531 --> 00:29.874
We're not talking about natural joy, but

00:29.986 --> 00:35.853
Christian joy, supernatural joy, real joy here this weekend.

00:37.896 --> 00:43.123
And I know in a room like this, some are thrilled for this theme.

00:44.204 --> 00:45.526
You love talking about joy.

00:45.586 --> 00:49.290
You experience joy that give me John Piper on joy.

00:49.310 --> 00:50.692
I want to talk about joy.

00:50.732 --> 00:58.482
And I'm sure there's some in this room that you'd rather not talk about joy this weekend

00:59.714 --> 01:08.947
because you've got some sorrow that landed on you this week, or you're in a season of sorrow, or you're undergoing suffering.

01:12.072 --> 01:12.913
And this is for you.

01:13.894 --> 01:22.527
Real joy is especially for you because the joy we're talking about this weekend is not joy that is exclusive of sorrow.

01:23.649 --> 01:24.690
If you suffer,

01:24.802 --> 01:27.064
If you have sorrow, this joy must be gone.

01:27.104 --> 01:30.247
No, this is a joy that is deeper than sorrow.

01:31.329 --> 01:33.671
So it can hold you up in sorrow.

01:34.572 --> 01:36.354
It's stronger than sorrow.

01:36.374 --> 01:39.937
It coexists with your sorrow and your suffering.

01:40.938 --> 01:46.884
So the Apostle Paul could say that we're sorrowful, yet we're always rejoicing.

01:47.325 --> 01:48.346
That's real joy.

01:49.607 --> 01:52.690
Comes in and alongside and sustains you.

01:52.770 --> 01:54.052
in your sorrow and suffering.

01:54.072 --> 01:55.393
So that's you this weekend.

01:55.974 --> 01:56.815
This is for you.

01:57.977 --> 01:59.779
Real joy is for you.

01:59.879 --> 02:03.284
It will uphold you in life's most difficult times.

02:04.966 --> 02:13.757
Now, one of the ways to talk about what we want to focus on this weekend is the term Christian hedonism.

02:14.959 --> 02:20.466
I need to put on your thinking cap here with me for just a minute because I know that hedonism

02:20.770 --> 02:24.796
is not a normal word that people are using on the streets of Gothenburg.

02:25.697 --> 02:26.959
That's not true in the States.

02:27.039 --> 02:29.622
It's not true in Sweden, all the Nordic area.

02:30.443 --> 02:31.845
It's a philosophical term.

02:32.726 --> 02:35.991
There may have been a time decades ago where it was more commonly used.

02:36.912 --> 02:43.261
Hedonism, that's built on the Greek word, hedeos, meaning pleasure.

02:43.281 --> 02:49.810
A hedonist is someone who, it's a philosophy of life,

02:50.690 --> 02:56.576
where they treat personal immediate pleasure as the highest good and proper aim of life.

02:58.498 --> 03:02.782
If that's the hedonism you're talking about, we're talking about, that's not Christian.

03:04.203 --> 03:09.348
That term Christian hedonism, that's provocative.

03:10.109 --> 03:11.230
That's strange.

03:12.111 --> 03:19.058
But if hedonism means something like a life devoted to pleasure,

03:19.810 --> 03:29.801
a very general definition of hedonism, a life devoted to pleasure, then that might leave room for the adjective Christian.

03:31.042 --> 03:42.254
That might be qualified by Christian, and it might give us an essential insight into an aspect of Christianity that we might be prone to overlook.

03:42.975 --> 03:49.362
That's what I'm after this weekend, an essential insight into the very nature of Christianity.

03:49.922 --> 03:56.991
and the gospel and the work of Jesus and our God with this provocative term, Christian hedonism.

03:58.072 --> 04:00.415
You might rather say hedonistic Christianity.

04:00.675 --> 04:01.877
You might want to say no term at all.

04:01.897 --> 04:02.377
That's fine.

04:02.397 --> 04:09.126
Not here to push a term, but to offer an essential insight into the nature of our faith.

04:10.067 --> 04:13.791
Just call it joy seeking Christianity.

04:18.397 --> 04:19.218
My hope

04:20.290 --> 04:49.266
after this weekend is that by looking at this particular central biblical emphasis that you will see the God of real joy with freshness, with new depth, and there would be greater worship that would spring up in your heart and that you'd be willing to take greater risks when you go back in conversation

04:50.082 --> 05:00.893
various acts that you may do, acts of love in your community because of this kind of joy-seeking emphasis that we want to draw out here in scripture this weekend.

05:02.594 --> 05:05.237
And I realize this may be a particular challenge to Swedes.

05:07.139 --> 05:18.130
At least in Minnesota, Swedish immigrants are known as being reserved and dignified and self-controlled and unemotional

05:19.682 --> 05:22.526
There are other nations that are known for being emotional.

05:23.507 --> 05:24.108
Swedes aren't.

05:24.789 --> 05:25.930
Is that just a Nordic thing?

05:26.811 --> 05:27.432
Nordic thing?

05:28.453 --> 05:29.975
We got to survive these winters.

05:31.037 --> 05:33.480
We can't waste energy on being overly emotional.

05:36.744 --> 05:44.434
And so it's all the sweeter to talk about supernatural Christian joy in Sweden.

05:46.690 --> 05:55.580
Here's some of what I have in mind as we talk about this essential joy-seeking impulse in biblical Christianity.

05:56.942 --> 06:00.206
At the very heart of our faith is Jesus.

06:01.247 --> 06:02.028
That's why we're here.

06:02.849 --> 06:03.690
We're here for Jesus.

06:05.152 --> 06:11.118
And Jesus appeals to his followers again and again on the basis of their joy.

06:11.739 --> 06:14.162
He says, your reward in heaven is great.

06:15.010 --> 06:19.316
and your father who sees in secret will reward you.

06:21.540 --> 06:22.801
What are you doing, Jesus?

06:23.603 --> 06:28.910
When you appeal to people's joy like that, that's a promise of reward.

06:28.930 --> 06:35.039
That's an appeal to pleasure and appeal to real joy.

06:36.541 --> 06:39.626
Joy now, enjoy eternally.

06:41.228 --> 06:42.450
And the Apostle Paul,

06:42.946 --> 06:48.112
In Acts 20, verse 35, he says, remember the words of Jesus.

06:49.113 --> 06:54.479
How he himself taught us, it is more blessed to give than to receive.

06:56.121 --> 06:56.802
More blessed.

06:57.703 --> 07:00.045
That means more happy.

07:01.307 --> 07:01.927
It's happier.

07:03.109 --> 07:04.570
You will be more joyful.

07:05.411 --> 07:11.538
You will experience real joy when you give to others rather than trying to take from them.

07:13.602 --> 07:15.926
Paul appeals to our joy.

07:15.986 --> 07:21.254
And how did Jesus himself endure the cross?

07:23.818 --> 07:24.719
This is what I want.

07:24.779 --> 07:32.611
This is what was most significant to me 20 years ago as I was hearing these truths for the first time that we'll talk about this weekend.

07:33.332 --> 07:36.497
What I wanted to know is how did Jesus endure the cross?

07:37.359 --> 07:39.602
What sustained Jesus

07:39.778 --> 07:44.823
in the greatest achievement in the history of the world that secured our salvation.

07:45.123 --> 07:45.704
I want that.

07:45.744 --> 07:46.605
I want to live that way.

07:48.286 --> 07:48.687
What is it?

07:50.008 --> 07:57.335
And Hebrews 12, 2 says, for the joy that was set before him, he endured the cross.

07:58.656 --> 08:00.858
And tomorrow morning, we're going to linger over that.

08:01.419 --> 08:09.106
Tomorrow morning, we spend time in the life of Jesus, seeing how he sought his father's glory and his own and his joy.

08:11.426 --> 08:18.915
And we have the Apostle Paul who said to the Philippians, to me, to live as Christ and to die is gain.

08:20.177 --> 08:20.637
Gain.

08:22.360 --> 08:23.541
That's joy language.

08:24.462 --> 08:25.964
That's pleasure-seeking.

08:26.024 --> 08:27.526
Gain.

08:27.606 --> 08:33.353
It would be gain, Paul said, if I depart and be with Christ, because Christ is far better.

08:34.034 --> 08:34.635
He's gain.

08:35.616 --> 08:40.562
And so he said, I count everything is lost in view of the surpassing

08:40.642 --> 08:43.847
value of knowing Christ Jesus, my Lord.

08:43.967 --> 08:45.269
That's the hedonism.

08:45.449 --> 08:48.634
That's the joy seeking I want to have of the Apostle Paul.

08:49.014 --> 08:53.921
And tonight we get the joy seeking prophet Isaiah.

08:56.485 --> 09:07.922
He says, all who thirst come to the waters, all who hunger come here to eat, enjoy wine and milk

09:08.354 --> 09:09.455
free of charge.

09:09.695 --> 09:11.417
If you're hungry, come feed here.

09:13.500 --> 09:16.703
Feed on true bread that truly satisfies.

09:17.704 --> 09:24.632
Eat what is good, delight yourself in rich fare, feast, enjoy, find pleasure here.

09:24.692 --> 09:30.479
That's Isaiah's hedonistic, joy-seeking call.

09:33.162 --> 09:37.106
I want you to see this for yourself in Isaiah 55.

09:37.858 --> 09:39.180
elsewhere throughout the Bible.

09:39.200 --> 09:43.745
I want you to see it in Hebrews and Paul, Jesus.

09:44.506 --> 09:53.918
So I want to word these principles tonight as we move through Isaiah 55, word these in such a way that they are whole Bible principles.

09:54.679 --> 09:55.680
They're here in Isaiah 55.

09:55.880 --> 10:02.508
I want to show you them here in Isaiah 55, but we're wording them in such a way as these are whole Bible truths.

10:03.970 --> 10:07.314
So these are three life shaping truths.

10:08.418 --> 10:26.816
from Isaiah 55 and that rocked my world as a 19-year-old in college in Greenville, South Carolina and have continued to rock my world and shape my world and give me real joy for 25 years.

10:29.318 --> 10:37.586
Number one, God made the world and you for His glory.

10:38.978 --> 10:43.485
God made the world and you for His glory.

10:44.426 --> 10:45.448
We'll start at the bottom.

10:46.650 --> 10:47.831
Go to verse 13.

10:49.294 --> 10:51.477
And verse 13 is a glimpse of the end.

10:51.517 --> 10:54.241
It's future for Isaiah, and it's future for us too.

10:54.762 --> 10:57.085
This is the end when God brings about a new heavens and new earth.

10:58.608 --> 11:08.082
And we see what God has been up to all along in creation, in His providence, in sustaining the world, and what He brings it all to a climax at in verse 13.

11:09.218 --> 11:11.862
Instead of the thorn shall come up the cypress.

11:13.484 --> 11:22.216
Instead of the briar shall come up the Myrtle and it shall make a name for the Lord.

11:23.058 --> 11:26.502
An everlasting sign that shall not be cut off.

11:30.087 --> 11:37.618
Now for our Bible students and readers, see that mention of thorns.

11:39.650 --> 11:41.513
What does that bring to mind biblically?

11:42.093 --> 11:42.594
Thorns.

11:44.797 --> 11:45.999
Well, a couple of places.

11:46.019 --> 11:47.721
I want Jesus wore a crown of thorns.

11:49.423 --> 12:01.420
Another is Genesis chapter three, verse 18, where God says to Adam after he sinned, cursed is the ground because of you, because of your sin.

12:01.480 --> 12:06.366
Thorns and thistles, it shall bring forth for you.

12:07.668 --> 12:09.010
So thorns,

12:09.570 --> 12:14.796
are a mark of God's curse on the world because of human sin.

12:16.718 --> 12:22.604
Whenever you come across a thorn in your garden or in the park, that's a reminder.

12:22.764 --> 12:25.887
This world is cursed because of our sin.

12:27.369 --> 12:28.290
We share in that.

12:30.813 --> 12:39.442
In Isaiah's vision of the new earth, he sees there that instead of the thorn comes up the cypress.

12:39.682 --> 12:51.394
Instead of the Briar, the Myrtle, and don't know how good you are on your horticulture, but Cyprus's and Myrtle's are evergreens.

12:53.395 --> 12:54.717
They're beautiful trees.

12:54.737 --> 12:56.198
They're not weeds.

12:56.218 --> 13:00.362
It's got to trees you want.

13:00.382 --> 13:02.885
And the point is the greatness of our God.

13:04.286 --> 13:08.210
Just as thorns remind us of human sin, so

13:08.354 --> 13:20.886
the replacing of those storms with evergreens will display and show the glory of God who overcomes our sin and overcomes the curse because of our sin.

13:22.708 --> 13:29.795
And God will remake the world, Isaiah says, to make a name for himself.

13:31.036 --> 13:34.920
That is another way of saying to glorify himself.

13:34.940 --> 13:35.940
He's doing it for his glory.

13:36.321 --> 13:37.522
That's why he made the world.

13:37.986 --> 13:40.970
And that's why he'll remake the world when Jesus returns.

13:42.753 --> 13:58.255
So he says earlier in Isaiah chapter 43 about his people, bring my sons from afar and my daughters from the end of the earth, everyone who is called by my name, whom I created for my glory, whom I formed and made.

14:00.177 --> 14:06.226
His people, Isaiah says, are for God's glory, for his name.

14:06.946 --> 14:09.609
And His world is for His glory.

14:11.772 --> 14:18.240
But perhaps we've heard that phrase, the glory of God, so often that it gets lost on us.

14:20.322 --> 14:29.533
I grew up in church, and I remember hearing the phrase, the glory of God, and singing songs like, to God be the glory.

14:30.575 --> 14:34.479
So many songs, proclaim His glory, sing of His glory.

14:34.580 --> 14:36.562
We talk about glorifying God.

14:37.762 --> 14:40.045
it can become white noise to us.

14:40.886 --> 14:47.454
Especially if you're growing up with it, you're too young to really understand what's meant by glorifying God, making a name for Him.

14:47.514 --> 14:55.504
And as I got older and started to read the Bible for myself, I realized, this is no small theme.

14:55.544 --> 15:06.418
This is all over the Bible, everywhere, for His glory, for His name, for His praise, for His honor,

15:07.298 --> 15:09.882
It's different ways of getting at the same concept.

15:10.783 --> 15:13.186
This is why God does all that He does.

15:13.246 --> 15:15.529
He created for His glory.

15:15.850 --> 15:18.033
He upholds the world for His glory.

15:18.273 --> 15:19.875
He sent His Son for His glory.

15:20.116 --> 15:21.758
Jesus died for His glory.

15:21.938 --> 15:25.683
He rescues us for His glory, and He will remake the world for His glory.

15:25.724 --> 15:36.178
And so as Jonathan Edwards summed it up 300 years ago, he said,

15:36.706 --> 15:42.392
all that is ever spoken of in the Scripture as God's ultimate end.

15:42.632 --> 15:51.462
That's His final goal, His highest aim is included in that one phrase, the glory of God.

15:54.485 --> 16:06.418
If you want to know the true God, and if you want to better understand the world in which you live, you need to know that God does all He does,

16:06.818 --> 16:08.941
for His glory.

16:12.365 --> 16:18.093
And that means He wants us as His creatures to do all we do to His glory.

16:18.113 --> 16:28.127
1 Corinthians 1031, whether you eat or whether you drink or whatever you do, do all to the glory of God.

16:30.931 --> 16:36.498
We're going to come back to verse 13 in a minute because we need to see what that word it.

16:36.866 --> 16:38.348
That's our key tonight.

16:38.969 --> 16:43.055
If you want to mark it and put your finger there, we need to know what the it is.

16:43.255 --> 16:51.487
What's the it in verse 13 that will make a name for God that will glorify God.

16:51.587 --> 16:59.198
But for now, see that God made the world and he made you and one day he'll remake the world for his glory.

16:59.919 --> 17:00.580
That's number one.

17:02.022 --> 17:03.965
He does all he does for his glory.

17:04.225 --> 17:04.786
Number two.

17:06.786 --> 17:25.089
God made you to long for and seek real joy, or you could say pursue satisfaction, our subtitle in our theme, pursuing satisfaction in God.

17:27.612 --> 17:30.976
This is more surprising to many Christians than truth number one.

17:33.779 --> 17:35.922
God made you to desire

17:36.386 --> 17:36.947
happiness.

17:38.469 --> 17:39.550
You want to be happy.

17:40.872 --> 17:42.234
You long to be happy.

17:43.596 --> 17:46.821
You seek unavoidably to find satisfaction.

17:46.881 --> 17:49.604
You want to have real joy.

17:53.610 --> 17:58.377
The philosopher and mathematician Blaze Pascal put it like this.

17:59.138 --> 18:00.660
Many other philosophers have echoed it.

18:02.562 --> 18:03.684
It's true biblically as well.

18:04.185 --> 18:05.106
He said it memorably.

18:06.594 --> 18:08.836
All men seek happiness.

18:09.997 --> 18:11.038
That is without exception.

18:12.520 --> 18:17.585
Whatever different means they employ, they all tend to this end.

18:17.645 --> 18:29.516
The cause of some going to war and of others avoiding it is the same desire for happiness in both, attended with different views.

18:31.158 --> 18:35.762
The will never takes the least step but to this object.

18:36.930 --> 18:44.220
This is the motive of every action of every man, even of those who hang themselves.

18:47.404 --> 18:49.287
All men seek happiness.

18:50.068 --> 18:56.997
God made you for real joy, to want real joy, to long to be happy, and you can't avoid it.

18:58.880 --> 19:00.202
In that longing, here's the key.

19:00.882 --> 19:04.648
That longing is not bad, but good.

19:05.469 --> 19:06.450
It is God-given.

19:06.786 --> 19:07.928
It's God designed.

19:09.650 --> 19:19.405
In fact, what's clear as day in this great invitation of Isaiah 55 is that God Himself appeals to our happiness.

19:20.386 --> 19:21.948
He appeals to our joy.

19:23.210 --> 19:24.953
Did you hear how this chapter reads?

19:25.934 --> 19:26.856
And we'll go back through it.

19:27.637 --> 19:34.968
You know what good news it is that the God of heaven talks like He talks in verses one to three.

19:36.069 --> 19:36.530
That means

19:36.642 --> 19:41.927
He intends to give living water, refreshing living water to thirsty souls.

19:42.728 --> 19:47.252
He means to give soul-satisfying bread to the hungry.

19:49.615 --> 19:55.941
The God who made you doesn't stop in and say, hey, what's going on down there?

19:56.522 --> 19:57.422
Stop hungering.

19:58.443 --> 19:59.825
Stop being so thirsty.

19:59.845 --> 20:03.008
You humans, you hungry humans.

20:04.369 --> 20:05.170
That's not our God.

20:07.202 --> 20:12.630
Rather, he says, be hungry, be thirsty.

20:12.650 --> 20:15.274
I made you for that.

20:15.775 --> 20:23.025
I put that in your soul to long for real joy that you might find real joy.

20:23.045 --> 20:30.496
And I mean with my omnipotence of the Godhead to help you find real joy.

20:30.537 --> 20:36.946
The problem with humanity

20:37.314 --> 20:38.796
is not that we desire.

20:41.820 --> 20:43.642
The problem is not that we hunger and thirst.

20:45.704 --> 21:06.450
The problem, which is called sin, is that we take the desire and the hunger and the thirst for real joy meant for God Himself and we settle for thin, empty, fake joys or good joys

21:06.690 --> 21:12.458
Apart from him, rather than in him, as C.S.

21:12.498 --> 21:15.903
Lewis said, we are far too easily pleased.

21:18.287 --> 21:18.968
Here's how he said it.

21:19.629 --> 21:34.130
If we consider the unblushing promises of reward and the staggering nature of the rewards promised in the gospels, it would seem that our Lord finds our desires not too strong, but too weak.

21:35.490 --> 21:45.765
We are half-hearted creatures fooling about with drink and sex and ambition when infinite joy, real joy, is offered us.

21:46.706 --> 22:02.770
Like an ignorant child who wants to go on making mud pies in a slum, because he cannot imagine what is meant by the offer of a holiday at the sea, we are far too easily pleased.

22:06.882 --> 22:13.070
The opening verses of Isaiah 55 lead us to picture a street vendor.

22:15.414 --> 22:18.918
I'm sure there's street vendors in the Nordic world.

22:21.822 --> 22:28.411
Our family came across a street vendor just last August who was memorable with the Minnesota State Fair.

22:29.973 --> 22:31.175
It's a big deal in Minnesota.

22:32.597 --> 22:36.562
And outside the fair, different folks gather who don't have

22:36.738 --> 22:39.180
permission to sell their goods inside the fair.

22:40.141 --> 22:45.086
And so they're trying to offer me a bottle of water as I leave the fair.

22:46.527 --> 22:51.492
And one really memorable street vendor says, you got a thirst?

22:52.613 --> 22:53.534
Come to me first.

22:54.775 --> 22:55.576
I'm your water guy.

22:57.337 --> 22:58.238
I said, I like that.

22:59.780 --> 23:03.123
If I wanted to water right now, you'd be my water guy because you rhyme.

23:03.763 --> 23:06.546
I like that you rhyme first and first.

23:06.882 --> 23:07.803
I'm a word guy.

23:07.823 --> 23:08.444
I love rhymes.

23:08.464 --> 23:08.984
Good job.

23:10.365 --> 23:10.966
Street vendor.

23:13.829 --> 23:26.602
What's so amazing about Isaiah 55 is that God Almighty humbles himself in Isaiah 55 to be a street vendor.

23:28.363 --> 23:30.826
You're like, that's what he's doing.

23:30.846 --> 23:31.747
Is anyone thirsty?

23:33.789 --> 23:34.930
I know you're thirsty.

23:35.458 --> 23:36.760
I made you to thirst.

23:38.042 --> 23:38.622
Listen up.

23:38.803 --> 23:44.711
All who thirst come drink my cold, clear, refreshing water.

23:44.751 --> 23:51.500
All who need strength drink my nourishing, vitamin rich milk.

23:53.463 --> 23:57.609
All who need joy drink my exhilarating wine.

23:59.511 --> 24:04.338
Come by wine and milk without cost because it's been covered.

24:05.698 --> 24:06.539
It's not cheap.

24:07.080 --> 24:07.801
It's the best.

24:08.401 --> 24:10.784
And somebody else has paid the price to offer it to you freely.

24:12.346 --> 24:15.390
Come, find real joy.

24:16.571 --> 24:18.834
That's the call of Isaiah 55.

24:20.636 --> 24:26.103
And verse two tells us what we want, why we come, why we hear this voice.

24:27.545 --> 24:28.285
We want real joy.

24:29.167 --> 24:35.314
Why do you spend your money for that which is not bread and your labor for that which does not satisfy?

24:36.130 --> 24:38.774
That's another way of saying we long for real joy.

24:38.794 --> 24:43.722
We want to be satisfied, our souls long for satisfaction.

24:43.762 --> 24:48.049
So number one, God made the world and you for His glory.

24:49.251 --> 24:56.142
Number two, God also made you to long for and seek satisfaction.

24:57.784 --> 25:00.329
That's not a defect, that's design.

25:00.389 --> 25:03.794
And these two truths

25:04.162 --> 25:11.050
that were made to seek His glory and made to seek our joy are as clear as day in Scripture.

25:11.671 --> 25:13.113
And they're both here in Isaiah 55.

25:14.575 --> 25:30.274
And then now, number three, we get to the heart of what Christian hedonism claims and what I want to make plain in this first session tonight and then deepen and apply tomorrow.

25:33.037 --> 25:33.618
Number three,

25:35.298 --> 25:39.322
These are not two pursuits, but one.

25:42.285 --> 25:44.166
Not two pursuits, one.

